
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `head` baraye namayesh khat haye avaliye yek file be kar miravad. Be tore pishfarz, 10 khat az aval file ra neshan midahad.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `head -n [tedad]` --> 🔢 Ta'يين tedad khat haye namayeshi.  Masalan, `head -n 20 file.txt` 20 khat aval را namayesh midahad.
    🔹 `head -c [tedad]` --> ✂️ Namayesh tedad character haye moshakhas shode az aval file.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ head file.txt

    🔹 Namayesh 10 khat aval file.txt.

    $ head -n 5 file.txt

    🔹 Namayesh 5 khat aval file.txt.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ head -c 50 file.txt

    🔹 Faghat 50 character aval file.txt ra namayesh midahad. Dar vaghe yek nim-negahi be aval file mindazad.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `head` command displays the beginning lines of a file. By default, it shows the first 10 lines.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `head -n [number]` --> 🔢 Specify the number of lines to display. For example, `head -n 20 file.txt` displays the first 20 lines.
    🔹 `head -c [number]` --> ✂️ Display the specified number of characters from the beginning of the file.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ head file.txt

    🔹 Display the first 10 lines of file.txt.

    $ head -n 5 file.txt

    🔹 Display the first 5 lines of file.txt.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ head -c 50 file.txt

    🔹 Displays only the first 50 characters of file.txt. Essentially, it provides a sneak peek at the beginning of the file.

